Schema Design Decisions:
Why did you choose your partition key structure?
How many GSIs did you create and why?
What denormalization trade-offs did you make?
I chose the partition key as the paper category, for example "CATEGORY#cs.NE", because most of the common queries start from a specific field or research area.
The sort key includes the publish date and paper ID (like "2023-01-15#2301.12345") so that I can easily fetch the most recent papers within a category — this makes time-based queries very efficient.

I created three GSIs.
One for author access (to get papers by author),
one for keywords,
and one for publication date.
Each GSI supports a different access pattern without having to scan the whole table.
For denormalization, I stored author, keyword, and category info together inside each item. That means some data is repeated — for example, the same author name may appear in multiple items — but it makes reads much faster. The trade-off is basically between speed and storage cost, and I optimized for speed.



Denormalization Analysis:
Average number of DynamoDB items per paper
Storage multiplication factor
Which access patterns caused the most duplication?

On average, there are about three DynamoDB items per paper (one in the main table, plus two in GSIs).
The storage multiplication factor is roughly 3× since each item stores a similar amount of metadata.
The author-based queries caused the most duplication, because a single paper can have multiple authors, and each author entry needs its own GSI record.


